    "title": "Requesting and Reviewing Builds",
    "url": "/docs/Builds_Lore_NPCs/BLD-001_Build_Request_and_Review",
    "excerpt": "BLD 001 — Requesting and Reviewing Builds New to staff work? See the Plain language glossary for technical terms. 1. Purpose Plan, build, review, and approve world changes before they are opened to players. 2. Scope Spaw",
    "text": "BLD 001 — Requesting and Reviewing Builds New to staff work? See the Plain language glossary for technical terms. 1. Purpose Plan, build, review, and approve world changes before they are opened to players. 2. Scope Spawn, towns, kingdoms/empires areas, dungeons, roads, caves, event arenas, interiors, ships, NPC locations, and other staff created world content. 3. Who does what Requester: Defines purpose and gameplay needs. Build lead: Assigns builder, scope, palette, and review stages. Builder: Works within boundaries and records dependencies. Lore/gameplay reviewer: Confirms canon and gameplay function. Administrator: Approves production paste/large edit and technical safety. 4. Procedure 4.1 Build brief Before work begins, define: Name and purpose World/region and boundaries Intended player flow and capacity Required NPCs, shops, gates, claims, war/event functions, or redstone Style references, palette, age/condition, and lore context Spoiler classification Performance constraints Completion criteria and review owner 4.2 Work environment Use a build world, schematic, or isolated region for substantial work. Mark boundaries. Avoid modifying live player areas or official locations before approval. 4.3 Review stages 1. Blockout: Scale, silhouette, routes, entrances, and gameplay spaces. 2. Structural review: Palette, shape, terrain integration, accessibility, and sightlines. 3. Detail review: Interiors, lighting, decoration, signage, NPC positions, and atmosphere. 4. Technical review: Entity count, redstone, block entities, collision, spawn safety, WorldGuard/claims, and performance. 5. Final canon/gameplay review: Names, lore, secrets, routes, shops, event triggers, and player permissions. 4.4 Quality checks Players can enter/exit without traps unless intentional and approved. No unintended voids, exposed commands/signs, barriers, debug blocks, or staff chests. Lighting/spawning behavior is intentional. Important routes are readable without excessive signage. Builds do not reveal unannounced lore/features from public viewpoints. NPC interaction points are accessible and protected from obstruction. Large decorative entity/model use is justified. 4.5 Production move Follow BLD 002 for large edits. Take a backup/schematic of the destination. Paste with an appropriate air/replace strategy, verify terrain and nearby player content, then complete a walk through in survival/adventure like conditions. 4.6 Acceptance and handoff Record final location, schematic/source, dependencies, NPC IDs, protections, maintenance notes, and screenshots. The build is not complete until associated configuration/NPC/lore tasks are assigned. 5. When to get senior help Escalate overlap with player claims/content, major terrain replacement, canon conflict, performance risk, use of unlicensed assets, or a production paste without a verified rollback. 6. What to record Build brief and boundaries Review screenshots/notes Schematic/source location Destination backup Approval and production location Dependency/NPC/protection handoff 7. Final checklist Brief and boundaries approved Build created outside live risk area Blockout and style reviewed Technical/performance review passed Canon/gameplay review passed Destination backup/schematic ready Production walk through completed Dependencies and maintenance documented 8. Related guides BLD 002 LOR 001 NPC 001 CNT 001 OPS 003"
