    "excerpt": "LOR 001 — Approving Official Lore New to staff work? See the Plain language glossary for technical terms. 1. Purpose Decide what lore is official and keep new lore consistent with the Eldenstead world. 2. Scope Official ",
    "text": "LOR 001 — Approving Official Lore New to staff work? See the Plain language glossary for technical terms. 1. Purpose Decide what lore is official and keep new lore consistent with the Eldenstead world. 2. Scope Official lore pages, NPC dialogue, books, quests, locations, gods, factions, kingdoms/empires, events, item descriptions, forum canon, and marketing statements presented as factual world lore. 3. Who does what Lore writer: Drafts content and marks assumptions/open questions. Lore lead: Maintains canon index and reviews consistency. Gameplay/build owner: Confirms content can be implemented and experienced as intended. Founder: Approves major cosmology, world history, permanent faction, or central story changes. 4. Procedure 4.1 Classify content Official: Official and binding until formally revised. Soft canon: Approved interpretation that may be refined. Rumor/in world belief: A character or culture believes it; not guaranteed true. Player created lore: Belongs to player storytelling and is not official world canon unless adopted. Draft/unannounced: Internal only. 4.2 Lore proposal Include title, content type, affected canon, intended audience, where it appears, gameplay/build dependencies, spoiler level, and unresolved questions. 4.3 Consistency review Check names, dates, geography, culture, technology, magic, deity behavior, previous public statements, and existing item/NPC/location text. For divine/Whispering Heart content, preserve established boundaries and avoid giving ordinary NPCs impossible knowledge without explanation. 4.4 Approval levels Minor local dialogue/flavor consistent with canon: Lore Lead. Named location, recurring NPC, cultural practice, item backstory: Lore Lead plus relevant owner. Major deity, world history, cosmology, central faction, or retcon: Founder approval. Public release date or gameplay feature embedded in lore: Content/Founder approval. 4.5 Implementation packet Approved lore should include exact text, formatting/color codes if relevant, delivery location, NPC/item/book identifiers, pronunciation notes for important names, and whether players may quote/post it publicly. 4.6 Retcons Prefer additive clarification over erasing public history. When a retcon is necessary, record old canon, new canon, reason, affected content, migration steps, and whether a public explanation is needed. 4.7 Player lore Encourage player kingdoms/empires and characters while separating their claims from official server canon. Staff moderation should address rule violations, not whether a player's fictional interpretation is “correct,” unless it falsely presents itself as official canon. 5. When to get senior help Escalate contradictions involving central lore, proposed real world hate/harassment themes, sexual content involving minors, use of a player's work without permission, or lore that reveals unannounced systems/dates. 6. What to record Lore proposal and classification Canon references checked Reviewer/approver Final implementation text Dependencies and spoiler level Retcon record where applicable 7. Final checklist Content classification assigned Existing canon checked Gameplay/build dependencies confirmed Correct approval level obtained Exact final text stored Spoiler/public status marked Canon index updated Retcons propagated to affected content 8. Related guides BLD 001 NPC 001 CNT 001 FOR 001 WEB 001"
